faqs:
  - q: "Is grain-free dog food always more expensive than regular dog food?"
    a: "Usually yes, but not always by much. Budget grain-free options like Harringtons start at £2/kg, comparable to budget regular food. Premium grain-free (Orijen, Eden) costs £10-13/kg. However, grain-free tends to be more calorie-dense, so you often feed smaller portions — which partially offsets the higher cost per kg."
  - q: "Can I mix grain-free and regular dog food?"
    a: "Yes, mixing is fine and some owners do it to manage costs. The key is to transition gradually to avoid digestive upset, and ensure the combined diet meets your dog's nutritional needs. If you're mixing specifically to address a grain sensitivity, the benefit depends on how much grain the regular food contributes."
  - q: "Does grain-free dog food help with itchy skin?"
    a: "It can do, if your dog's skin issues are caused by a grain sensitivity. However, itchy skin in dogs is more commonly caused by environmental allergens or sensitivities to proteins like beef or chicken. A vet assessment before switching is worthwhile to make sure you're addressing the right cause."
  - q: "What grains are most commonly found in regular dog food?"
    a: "Wheat is the most common grain in UK dog food, followed by maize (corn), rice, oats, and barley. Of these, wheat is the most likely to cause sensitivities. Rice is generally the most digestible grain and rarely causes issues. If you want to avoid just wheat, you can find grain-inclusive foods that use rice instead."
  - q: "How long does it take to see a difference after switching to grain-free?"
    a: "Most owners see digestive improvements within 1-2 weeks. Skin and coat improvements take longer — typically 4-8 weeks. This is because skin cells turn over slowly. If you've seen no improvement after 8 weeks on a consistent grain-free diet, grain sensitivity is probably not the cause of your dog's symptoms."
